I thought it would be interesting to start a thread about unusual things that
happen at antique auctions. This occured at a farm auction about twenty years
ago. If you can't stand a very sad story don't read any further.
My family liked to spend weekends going to auctions in the nearby countryside
and small towns. You rarely found the finest of antiques, but we picked up some
good old quality wood funiture and the occasional boxed lot was still being
sold, which often contained a surprise, either good or bad.

One sunday, we were at a farm auction. The owner was an elderly gentleman whose
wife had died recently, and being in poor health himself, had decided to sell
off the farm and move across country to be closer to family. It was your
ordinary auction until close to the end. Up until then, farmer had been pretty
much in the background, chatting with neighbors but not envolved in any way. He
called his lassie-type dog over, and walked to the front of the auction, were
the auctioneers were, and announced to the crowd that he would not be able to
take his dog to his new home, and so was auctioning it off. He said she was a
real good dog, obedient and friendly. He then picked up his dog, and, holding
up in the air, began to silently cry. The auctioneer called for bids while the
elderly farmer held up the dog, tears rolling down his cheeks. The crowd stood
stunned and quiet, until one man finally bid $5, and got the dog. It was the
saddest thing we had ever seen at an auction. Any others with a story?
Susan

