An estate auction was held at a farm that had been in the same family for many
generations. The event was well publicized and
drew a lot of buyers, some with very deep pockets. A set of sleigh bells came up,
and the bidding was between a well dressed
man and an old farmer. The farmer really wanted those bells. I watched his face,
and as he dropped out at $700, it was
obvious that his heart was broken. I'm sure that he had some emotional connection
to those bells, but never did find out for
sure. I hope that I never want something so bad that I'll step on true human
emotions to get it.

On the other hand, I don't think that auctions such as those described in this
thread are totally sad. Ultimately, the items sold
will end up with someone who appreciates them, instead of being in boxes somewhere,
neglected by uncaring heirs.

Jan

