When my Mom died my brothers and sisters decided that I had the most experience
in pricing &quot;old things.&quot; So I was assigned the task of placing a monetary
value on everything. Then anyone who wanted something had that amount charged
to their &quot;account.&quot; In the end those who took things of least value got more
cash to even it out. The only thing I would not price was a Victorian Table
which had been given new as a weding present to my grandparents. I wanted it
and I didn't want anyone complaining later that I set the price. My brother
did that and since it was the only thing I wanted no one contested with me for
it. There were several things that more than one person wanted. The ulimate
owner was decided among the contenders. Sometimes a coin toss was used but
more often it was who had the greatest sentimental attachment. At the end of
the day everyone was satisfied.

